	<div class="the_hub_content_wrapper the_hub_article">
		<div class="the_hub_content">
		<a href="/category/the-hub/" class="header_link">
		<div class="the_hub_title_wrapper">
			<div class="the_hub_logo">
				<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/plugins/lb-content-widgets/img/lit-horn.svg">
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_title">
				<h1>The Hub</h1>
			</div>
			<div class="the_hub_slogan">
				<h1>News, Notes, Talk</h1>
			</div>
		</div>
		</a>
		
				<div class="the_hub_item">
			<div class="banner_img">
				<a href="https://lithub.com/a-beach-boys-inspired-reading-list-11-books-to-fuel-a-weird-beautiful-summer/" title="A Beach Boys-inspired reading list: </br>11 books to fuel a weird, beautiful summer.">
		    		<img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/brian-wilson.jpg" alt="" class="post_ft entry_post"/>
		    	</a>
			</div>
			
			<div class="post_content">
				<h1 data-report-url="/a-beach-boys-inspired-reading-list-11-books-to-fuel-a-weird-beautiful-summer/"><a href="https://lithub.com/a-beach-boys-inspired-reading-list-11-books-to-fuel-a-weird-beautiful-summer/">A Beach Boys-inspired reading list: </br>11 books to fuel a weird, beautiful summer.</a></h1>
				
				<div class="author_info">
					<div class="author_photo"><img src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/james-folta-scaled-e1711473313743-100x100.jpg" width="100" height="100" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2024/03/james-folta-scaled-e1711473313743-300x300.jpg 2x" alt="James Folta" class="avatar avatar-100 wp-user-avatar wp-user-avatar-100 alignnone photo" /></div>
					<div class="author_name">By&nbsp;<a href="https://lithub.com/author/jamesfolta/" itemprop="url"><span itemprop="name">James&nbsp;Folta</span></a></div>
					<div class="author_hr"><hr/></div>
					<div class="publish_date">June 17, 2025, 2:22pm</div>
				</div>
				
				<p style="text-align: right;"><em>Photo from <a href="https://www.brianwilson.com/1966" class="external" target="_blank">brianwilson.com</a></em></p>
<p>Beach Boy Brian Wilson, the American genius and <a href="https://www.spin.com/2017/05/its-been-ten-years-since-brian-wilson-said-his-favorite-movie-was-norbit/" class="external" target="_blank">big time <em>Norbit</em> fan</a>, passed away last week. He wrote some of the greatest pop songs of all time, and to honor the departed musician, I’ve curated a playlist/reading list of tunes and books to pack along the next time you’re heading to the beach.</p>
<p><iframe title="YouTube video player" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/sT8FTWrYG6A?si=QlKvAwW6SN-wPHcw" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Listen to: “Surfin’ U.S.A.” </strong>Let&#8217;s start with this classic, early ‘60s ear worm. It&#8217;s pretty saccharine though—why not temper it with something on the darker side of surfing?</p>
<p><img fetchpriority="high" decoding="async" data-attachment-id="116203" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/20-perfect-summer-books-for-this-and-every-year/attachment/18693910/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/18693910.jpg" data-orig-size="270,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="William Finnegan, Barbarian Days" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/18693910-203x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/18693910.jpg" class="aligncenter wp-image-116203 size-medium" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/18693910-203x300.jpg" alt="William Finnegan, Barbarian Days" width="203" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/18693910-203x300.jpg 203w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2019/06/18693910.jpg 270w" sizes="(max-width: 203px) 100vw, 203px" /></p>
<p><strong>Pair with: William Finnegan’s memoir <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780143109396" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Barbarian Days</em></a></strong> will make you want to experience Finnegan’s ecstatic connection to surfing, and also fear the extremes of surf culture. I like to imagine the <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=JDRNaAxryu8" class="external" target="_blank">“ride the barrel and get pitted”</a> guy was on the Pulitzer committee for this one.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="45256" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/an-endless-summer-of-the-best-in-surf-lit/tappingsource/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tappingsource.jpg" data-orig-size="300,446" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="tappingsource" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tappingsource-202x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tappingsource.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-45256" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tappingsource-202x300.jpg" alt="" width="202" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tappingsource-202x300.jpg 202w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tappingsource-100x150.jpg 100w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/tappingsource.jpg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 202px) 100vw, 202px" /></p>
<p>Nothing says “surfing” and “USA” like sadistic beach freaks and crazed ‘Nam vets. <strong>Kem Nunn’s </strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781451645545" class="external" target="_blank"><strong>Tapping the Source</strong></a> is a fun, feverish, sand-blasted noir that inspired <em>Point Break,</em> one of the top movies in the Boyfriend Film Canon.</p>
<p><iframe title="YouTube video player" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/j1THDLgL_bs?si=UJo4G0TCBFt7CxQN" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><strong>Listen to: “Help Me Rhonda” </strong>This deceptively sunny tune has some real heaviness beneath it: the deep guitars, the low “bow oh oh”s, and the rejected narrator pitching a weird love triangle. There are plenty of books out there about love triangles and men begging woman to sleep with them, going all the way back to <em>The Aeneid&#8217;s</em> self-serving lover boy, but how might Rhonda feel?</p>
<p style="text-align: left;"><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255827" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-beach-boys-inspired-reading-list-11-books-to-fuel-a-weird-beautiful-summer/attachment/9781250838193/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193.jpg" data-orig-size="667,1000" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="9781250838193" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255827" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193-40x60.jpg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193-33x50.jpg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/9781250838193.jpg 667w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p><strong>Pair with: </strong>Lise from <strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/p/books/faces-tove-ditlevsen/16943140?ean=9781250838193&amp;next=t" class="external" target="_blank">Tove Ditlevsen’s <em>Faces</em></a></strong> is a quintessential heartsick and confused character to me, who is looking for some relief too. I think Lise might see herself in the opening lines: “Well, since she put me down I&#8217;ve been out doin&#8217; in my head/I come in late at night and in the mornin&#8217; I just lay in bed.”</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="183398" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/defiant-women-and-defiant-books-a-reading-list/detransition-baby/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby.jpeg" data-orig-size="329,500" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="Detransition, Baby" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby-197x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby.jpeg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-183398" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby-197x300.jpeg" alt="Detransition, Baby" width="197" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby-197x300.jpeg 197w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby-39x60.jpeg 39w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2021/10/Detransition-Baby.jpeg 329w" sizes="(max-width: 197px) 100vw, 197px" /></p>
<p><strong>Torrey Peters’ <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593133385" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Detransition, Baby</em></a></strong> features another complex romantic entanglement, with characters after solace and love, and where everyone’s begging to “help me get her out of my heart.”</p>
<p><iframe title="YouTube video player" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/M0lj3WX_5ps?si=_3ThLbQpmF6YSF4O" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p><strong>Listen to: “God Only Knows”</strong></p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="101527" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/midwestern-women-an-essential-reading-list/gilead-marilynne-robinson/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson.jpg" data-orig-size="1400,2100" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="Gilead &#8211; Marilynne Robinson" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-200x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-683x1024.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-101527" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-200x300.jpg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-200x300.jpg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-768x1152.jpg 768w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson-683x1024.jpg 683w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2018/10/Gilead-Marilynne-Robinson.jpg 1400w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p><strong>Pair with: </strong>One of the greatest songs of all time needs to be paired with one of the greatest books of all time: <strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781250784018" class="external" target="_blank"><em>Gilead </em>by Marilynne Robinson</a>. </strong>Both are sweeping, reflective, hopeful, and appealing to a higher power: put these two American masterpieces in conversation.</p>
<p><iframe title="YouTube video player" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/apBWI6xrbLY?si=XLuPt5SXA2ABBD6B" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p><strong>Listen to: “Good Vibrations”</strong> What sticks out to me about &#8220;Good Vibrations&#8221; is how strangely patchwork it is: there are so many small compositions and moments that fit together in this trippy love song. I also love the invented word “excitations” here, a neologism that doesn’t seem to have caught on.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255834" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-beach-boys-inspired-reading-list-11-books-to-fuel-a-weird-beautiful-summer/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet.png" data-orig-size="527,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="miniature wife and doll&#8217;s alphabet" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet-300x228.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet.png" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255834" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet-300x228.png" alt="" width="300" height="228" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet-300x228.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet-60x46.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet-50x38.png 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/miniature-wife-and-dolls-alphabet.png 527w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p>
<p><strong>Pair with: </strong>This song reminds me of two dreamy and inventive short story collections: <strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781594632273" class="external" target="_blank"><em>The Miniature Wife by Manuel Gonzales</em></a>,</strong> which features a plane that circles for years and a man who speaks from his ears. and the smart horror in <strong><em><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781566894906" class="external" target="_blank">The Doll’s Alphabet by Camilla Grudova</a></em></strong>, with stories of a spider-man in Europe and a feminist revolution. Both are as weird and beautiful as Wilson&#8217;s song.</p>
<p><iframe title="YouTube video player" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/6Vv_dkDwZeQ?si=HBCCEnY-e6EOBRxy" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p><strong>Listen to: “Wouldn’t It Be Nice” </strong>Relationships are hard. Lyrically, this song is pretty simple, but the complexity of the musical arrangement elevates it to something more than just a ditty about teenage puppy love. This is a song about belonging, about imagining a future with someone, and feeling the pang of the distance between where you are and where you hope to be.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="251789" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/the-white-whales-of-the-sky-on-moby-dick-airplanes-and-obsessions-past-and-present/sky-daddy/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy.jpeg" data-orig-size="300,450" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="sky daddy" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy-200x300.jpeg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy.jpeg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-251789" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy-200x300.jpeg" alt="" width="200" height="300" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy-200x300.jpeg 200w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy-40x60.jpeg 40w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy-33x50.jpeg 33w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/04/sky-daddy.jpeg 300w" sizes="(max-width: 200px) 100vw, 200px" /></p>
<p><strong>Pair with: </strong>Naturally, this sends me to a book about finding love in <em>very</em> new places: <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780593231494" class="external" target="_blank"><strong>Kate Folk’s <em>Sky Daddy</em></strong></a>. Like the song, <em>Sky Daddy</em> is strange, sweet, and full of deep longing. Unlike the song though, this one features horniness for jet planes.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="35408" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-beach-boys-inspired-reading-list-11-books-to-fuel-a-weird-beautiful-summer/images-40/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/images2.jpg" data-orig-size="187,300" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;1&quot;}" data-image-title="city of quartz" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/images2-187x300.jpg" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/images2.jpg" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-35408" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2016/03/images2-187x300.jpg" alt="" width="187" height="300" /></p>
<p>And if we’re talking about Californians striving for a better world, a “world where we belong,” <strong>Mike Davis’ </strong><a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9781786635891" class="external" target="_blank"><em><strong>City of Quartz</strong></em></a> has to be in the conversation.</p>
<p><iframe title="YouTube video player" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/216YJKbber8?si=sU1XZRGulVCs24Dm" width="560" height="315" frameborder="0" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen"></iframe></p>
<p><strong>Listen to: “I Just Wasn’t Made for These Times”</strong> Brian Wilson was a man who struggled, and I think probably felt pretty out of step much of the time. But there isn&#8217;t much bitterness in this song, and like many Beach Boys songs, the complexity of the music complicate the meaning. This is a lament for something that is out of reach, almost strange to the narrator.</p>
<p><img decoding="async" data-attachment-id="255836" data-permalink="https://lithub.com/a-beach-boys-inspired-reading-list-11-books-to-fuel-a-weird-beautiful-summer/kobo-abe/" data-orig-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe.png" data-orig-size="536,400" data-comments-opened="1" data-image-meta="{&quot;aperture&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;credit&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;camera&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;caption&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;created_timestamp&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;copyright&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;focal_length&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;iso&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;shutter_speed&quot;:&quot;0&quot;,&quot;title&quot;:&quot;&quot;,&quot;orientation&quot;:&quot;0&quot;}" data-image-title="kobo-abe" data-image-description="" data-image-caption="" data-medium-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe-300x224.png" data-large-file="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe.png" class="aligncenter size-medium wp-image-255836" src="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe-300x224.png" alt="" width="300" height="224" srcset="https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe-300x224.png 300w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe-60x45.png 60w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe-50x37.png 50w, https://s26162.pcdn.co/wp-content/uploads/2025/06/kobo-abe.png 536w" sizes="(max-width: 300px) 100vw, 300px" /></p>
<p><strong>Pair with: </strong>When I think of characters who are “looking for a place to fit in&#8221; and who “got brains but they ain&#8217;t doing…no good,” I think of the great <strong>Kobo Abe</strong>&#8216;s books. Particularly, the man and woman in <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780679733782" class="external" target="_blank"><em><strong>The Woman in the Dunes</strong></em></a><em><strong>,</strong></em> and The Box Man from <a href="https://bookshop.org/a/132/9780375726514" class="external" target="_blank"><strong><em>The Box Man</em></strong></a><em>,</em> who dons a large cardboard box, retreating into a strange reality all his own.</p>
<p>Sometimes if the world is too strange and frightening, we have to find ways to make something new. Rest in peace, Brian.</p>
